WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.720
So happy Thursday, everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:17.240
Hope everybody's having a great week.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:18.240
I'm Rachel.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:23.600
If we haven't met yet, let us know if it's your first time joining, you want to say hello

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:27.660
in the chat so we can all welcome you in together.

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:32.779
This is an open space to chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing,

00:00:32.779 --> 00:00:37.700
and getting to hear about what's going on in the world of data across different industries.

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:42.380
And so every week, we feature a different data science leader as my co host to help

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:46.660
us lead the discussion and answer questions from you all.

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:50.740
Together we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for everybody.

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:55.259
And I love to hear from everyone, no matter your level of experience or area of work.

00:00:55.259 --> 00:00:59.580
It is totally okay just to listen in if you want.

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:03.259
There's always three ways that you can ask questions, though, and also provide your own

00:01:03.259 --> 00:01:05.540
perspective on certain topics.

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:10.699
So you can always jump in by raising your hand on Zoom.

00:01:10.699 --> 00:01:13.459
You can put questions in the Zoom chat.

00:01:13.459 --> 00:01:16.779
And feel free to just put like a little star next to it if you want me to read it if you're

00:01:16.779 --> 00:01:18.959
in a coffee shop or something.

00:01:18.959 --> 00:01:23.820
And then we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:28.660
And Hannah will share that in the chat here in just a second again.

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:30.900
We do share the recordings of each session.

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:37.180
So they'll be up on the Posit YouTube, as well as the data science Hangout site.

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:41.860
But with all that, thank you so much, Regis, for joining us as our co host today.

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:49.620
Regis James is a senior manager of biopharmaceutical data science at Regeneron Pharmaceuticals.

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:53.339
And Regis, I'd love to have you introduce yourself and maybe start off by sharing a

00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:58.099
little bit about your role and something you like to do outside of work, too.

00:01:58.099 --> 00:01:59.300
Sure.

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:00.300
Thanks for having me.

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:05.260
Let's see a little bit about my role and what I like to do outside.

00:02:05.260 --> 00:02:12.500
So I've been on the side of the company that I'm on right now for almost nine months.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:18.179
But before that, and I'll kind of clarify what I mean by that, I came to Regeneron right

00:02:18.179 --> 00:02:25.860
out of my Ph.D. in 2016, and I was on the R&D side and I did a lot of collaborations

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:33.100
with biologists who were generating tons of data, but it was kind of challenging to make

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:35.660
decisions based on that data.

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:43.059
So what I did a lot was distill things down to their fundamentals to simplify the process

00:02:43.059 --> 00:02:45.899
of going from stuck to unstuck.

00:02:45.899 --> 00:02:50.740
And in June of last year, I moved over to be a bit closer to the patients, which has

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:56.699
always been my passion ever since before I went to undergrad for bioengineering.

00:02:56.699 --> 00:02:58.979
But I wanted to be closer to the clinical trial side.

00:02:58.979 --> 00:03:00.259
So that's where I am now.

00:03:00.259 --> 00:03:05.699
And I'm working to help optimize clinical trials using AI and ML.

00:03:05.699 --> 00:03:09.179
But there are a lot of different parts of the side of the company that I've moved to,

00:03:09.179 --> 00:03:13.179
which is called global development, that are not just clinical trials.

00:03:13.179 --> 00:03:16.660
There are a whole bunch of other things.

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:20.940
And we are in the process of figuring out how to establish some of these collaborations

00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:22.940
with them as well.

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:29.580
I also have, since the time that I was on the R&D side, have been maintaining a community

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.339
of data scientists that are around the entire company.

00:03:32.339 --> 00:03:37.020
And since Regeneron is global, it's actually a global organization.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:42.899
And the reason why this organization formed was because when I came right out of my PhD,

00:03:42.899 --> 00:03:51.259
the ecosystem that I used was R. And RStudio now posits environment of the RStudio IDE

00:03:51.259 --> 00:03:55.820
and Chinese Server Pro, which has now been evolved into RStudio Connect.

00:03:55.820 --> 00:04:01.220
So I needed to get that set up so that I could do the same level of collaborations with non-computational

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:05.139
people that I did during my grad school work, but at Regeneron.

00:04:05.139 --> 00:04:07.740
So when I set that up, other people heard about it and they were like,

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:10.339
oh my gosh, this is amazing. Can we please do this?

00:04:10.339 --> 00:04:12.619
So then I started letting people on.

00:04:12.619 --> 00:04:17.059
But I don't want to say with great power comes great responsibility,

00:04:17.059 --> 00:04:24.660
but with great open source access comes great responsibility to support an ongoing community of people.

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:28.260
So that ended up happening.

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:34.500
And what people were doing was building shiny apps and a whole bunch of different other types of analytics

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:37.059
that they were sharing with non-computational colleagues.

00:04:37.059 --> 00:04:41.700
And so I started hosting these showcases that would show, I hadn't mentioned this part to you, Rachel,

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:45.980
but that would show what people had been building.

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:50.019
And then they would kind of show it to a range of people around the company, which was kind of,

00:04:50.019 --> 00:04:53.380
it was feeding, it was a positive feedback loop because people started understanding,

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:56.700
as my current boss calls it, the art of possible.

00:04:56.700 --> 00:04:59.380
So then they were like, wait, that's, does that mean we can do this?

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:04.179
And can we do that? Can we do that? So then it kind of started growing.

00:05:04.179 --> 00:05:08.940
So then I was only working in the R side and supporting that community.

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:12.140
But then similarly, I can't remember which one happened first,

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:15.500
but it was very close in time to when RStudio was like,

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:18.739
there's other people in the world who use data science.

00:05:18.739 --> 00:05:24.420
I mean, the IDE, the workbench always supported a broad range of languages,

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:28.619
but to make it more formally cross language,

00:05:28.619 --> 00:05:33.140
that happened around the same time that I moved the group from just R people

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:37.899
to R and other programming languages that exist to enable data science.

00:05:37.899 --> 00:05:43.500
So that's the group that I convene every other Friday.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:47.859
And yeah, we're having one tomorrow. It's internal, of course, but we're,

00:05:47.859 --> 00:05:52.940
so it's, we talk about the problems that data scientists face and how we address them.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:56.820
And then it kind of often, especially this year,

00:05:56.820 --> 00:06:01.140
it's been triggering spinoff meetings of other people who have common problems

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:05.140
and they exist across the company. So it's been going pretty well.

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:12.380
In my free time, I mean, I am a lover of sci-fi things.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:19.500
So I have for a couple of years been working on a data science novel series

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:27.100
that takes all of the geeky, nerdy, awesome things like cryptocurrency and CRISPR

00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:33.299
and a whole bunch of different things and integrates them into what I think is going to be an interesting story.

00:06:33.299 --> 00:06:36.899
And I'm planning on releasing that at some point in the future.

00:06:36.899 --> 00:06:38.899
So that's what I do in my free time.

00:06:38.899 --> 00:06:46.420
And I've been able to influence or I've been able to attract my wife to also contribute.

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:47.820
And she's also a scientist.

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:55.179
So sometimes we have these like brainstorming sessions about different plot points that could happen

00:06:55.179 --> 00:06:58.339
and making them realistic, but also having a bunch of action in there too.

00:06:58.339 --> 00:07:01.779
So that's the thing I do in my free time with my favorite person.

00:07:01.779 --> 00:07:03.980
So I love it.

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:08.380
It sounds like you have a lot of people who want to buy that in the chat here right now.

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:18.059
So when that's out, I'll have to put it on the list of recommendations to all the books Libby's been collecting.

00:07:18.059 --> 00:07:24.500
But I'm so excited that you started off with community because that's something that I was going to ask you about as well,

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:28.940
because I was leading a community building workshop at R&Pharma.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:38.380
And during that workshop, I personally learned so much from you Regis and just wanted to be able to share that with everybody here too.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:46.260
But you just said that a lot of people start having these these spinoff meetings from the Friday sessions, which is amazing.

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:51.619
And I was just wondering, how do you help facilitate that within the community?

00:07:51.619 --> 00:07:59.100
So they haven't always been like the spinoffs have kind of started a little bit more recently.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:01.380
Sometimes there have been a thing here or there.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:04.500
I haven't, to be honest, and everything's a work in progress.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:08.339
The community is about helping each other figure out how to figure stuff out.

00:08:08.339 --> 00:08:12.859
So in the most recent spinoff, I wasn't exactly sure where my role was.

00:08:12.859 --> 00:08:14.579
They were like, thank you, Regis.

00:08:14.579 --> 00:08:16.660
We are together.

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:19.299
We're meeting each other because of the organization that you created.

00:08:19.299 --> 00:08:20.739
And I was like, yes, cool.

00:08:20.739 --> 00:08:23.059
But I'm still trying to figure out exactly what it is.

00:08:23.059 --> 00:08:25.739
And I mean, I don't think I should be in charge of everything.

00:08:25.739 --> 00:08:33.299
It's good for things to happen organically, but be triggered by existing problems that people have.

00:08:33.299 --> 00:08:42.460
The thing that happened recently without because, of course, I can't go into detail about what it was, but I can speak in general, but yet specific for this community data science terms.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:50.380
It was about natural language processing in different contexts to identify things that we need to act on.

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:54.659
And there are three different parts of the company that have the same problem.

00:08:54.659 --> 00:08:57.299
And we would not have come together without that.

00:08:57.299 --> 00:08:58.979
So people were asking questions.

00:08:58.979 --> 00:09:03.020
What I typically do, though, when I prep the speaker.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:05.500
So it's every other Friday.

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:09.619
And before last year, I was setting a meeting.

00:09:09.619 --> 00:09:11.500
Actually, I was doing it even more lightly.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:18.020
I was just messaging them on Microsoft Teams to say, hey, are you ready to have XYZ so that we can kind of share it with the community?

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:31.219
But as things have gotten more complicated and people's schedules have gotten crazier now, I I have my schedule set out for the whole year, basically until the end of twenty twenty three every other Friday, except for holidays.

00:09:31.219 --> 00:09:36.179
So now what I've done is I even have I have the page open right here on my other screen.

00:09:36.179 --> 00:09:43.940
I have a column of red, green and yellow icons indicating whether or not the schedule date is locked down or not.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:50.059
So whenever I have it locked down, when the person agrees, then I schedule the two weeks before.

00:09:50.059 --> 00:09:59.099
So not the Monday of the gathering, but the Monday before I I meet with them to make sure we have everything together.

00:09:59.099 --> 00:10:09.859
So so that it's really easy for the people who are in attendance to know what the walkaway scenario, what the takeaway point is, so they can apply it to their own work as quickly as possible.

00:10:09.859 --> 00:10:20.659
So I do a lot of honing there and I think it's been paying off because in the meetings, people have been really engaged and have been asking questions during the meetings because I've been able to whittle it down.

00:10:20.659 --> 00:10:24.619
The speaker that I have tomorrow, I said, I apologize.

00:10:24.619 --> 00:10:29.659
I don't mean to ask you to ruin your story, but it may be helpful if you'd say the end part at the beginning.

00:10:29.659 --> 00:10:33.020
And he's like, no, no, no, please, please. I do want to ruin it.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:41.700
So I think that would but but having them basically ruin their stories and saying the end at the beginning is what gets I think it helps people get engaged.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:48.739
So there were different departments that got engaged because of the way I was able to flip the narrative and say the ending from the beginning.

00:10:48.739 --> 00:10:57.260
And so because of that part, I think people were able to just jump in and identify things that were needed.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:05.700
And so kind of it's a long winded way of saying that I was sort of sitting and listening to the subgroup from the community talk.

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:12.380
I was involved in one of the projects that the that spun off that were discussed in the spinoff.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:17.700
